```java
import java.util.Scanner;
public class ProductRating {
    static int[] iPadRatings = new int[10];
    static int[] laptopRatings = new int[10];
    static int[] desktopRatings = new int[10];
    static int iPadIndex = 0;
    static int laptopIndex = 0;
    static int desktopIndex = 0;
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        while (true) {
            System.out.println("Enter a product to rate (iPad Pro, Laptop, Desktop) or type \"exit\" to quit:");
            String product = scanner.nextLine();
            if (product.equalsIgnoreCase("exit")) {
                break;
            }
            System.out.println("Enter a rating for " + product + " (1-10):");
            int rating = scanner.nextInt();
            scanner.nextLine();
            if (isValidRating(product, rating)) {
                switch (product.toLowerCase()) {
                    case "ipad pro":
                        iPadRatings[iPadIndex] = rating;
                        iPadIndex++;
                        break;
                    case "laptop":
                        laptopRatings[laptopIndex] = rating;
                        laptopIndex++;
                        break;
                    case "desktop":
                        desktopRatings[desktopIndex] = rating;
                        desktopIndex++;
                        break;
                }
            } else {
                System.out.println("Invalid rating for " + product + ". Please try again.");
            }
        }
        System.out.println("Average rating for iPad Pro: " + calculateAverage(iPadRatings, 0, 0));
        System.out.println("Average rating for Laptop: " + calculateAverage(laptopRatings, 0, 0));
        System.out.println("Average rating for Desktop: " + calculateAverage(desktopRatings, 0, 0));
    }
    public static boolean isValidRating(String product, int rating) {
        switch (product.toLowerCase()) {
            case "ipad pro":
                return rating % 2 == 0;
            case "laptop":
                return rating % 2 == 1;
            case "desktop":
                return isPrime(rating);
            default:
                return false;
        }
    }
    public static boolean isPrime(int number) {
        if (number <= 1) {
            return false;
        }
        for (int i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(number); i++) {
            if (number % i == 0) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
    public static double calculateAverage(int[] ratings, int index, double sum) {
        if (index == ratings.length) {
            return sum / ratings.length;
        }
        if (ratings[index] != 0) {
            sum += ratings[index];
        }
        return calculateAverage(ratings, index + 1, sum);
    }
}
```
Here's how the program works:
- The program starts by creating three arrays to store the ratings for each product, along with three index variables to keep track of where to store the next rating in each array.
- The program then enters a loop that prompts the user to enter a product to rate and a rating for that product. If the user enters "exit", the loop ends and the program moves on to calculating the average ratings.
- The isValidRating() method is used to validate the rating entered by the user. If the rating is valid, the program stores it in the appropriate array and increments the corresponding index variable. If the rating is invalid, the program displays an error message and prompts the user to enter a new rating.
- Once the user has entered all the ratings, the program uses a recursive algorithm to calculate the average rating for each product. The calculateAverage() method takes an array, an index, and a sum as parameters. The index variable is used to iterate over the array, and the sum variable is used to keep track of the total sum of all the ratings in the array. The method adds each rating to the sum if it is not equal to 0 (which indicates an empty slot in the array), and then calls itself with the next index and the updated sum. Once the method has iterated over the entire array, it returns the average rating by dividing the sum by the length of the array.
