To implement the dynamic navigation menu, we can use the following steps:

1. First, we need to create a container for the menu in the HTML page, where we will generate the menu items dynamically. Let's create a div with the ID "nav-menu" where we will generate the menu.

```
<div id="nav-menu"></div>
```

2. Next, we need to write JavaScript code that will generate the menu items dynamically based on the sections in the HTML page. We can use the `querySelectorAll` method to get all the section elements in the HTML page, and then create a hierarchical list of menu items using nested `ul` and `li` elements. We can also add the "undevelop.svg" icon to the menu items that have sub-sections. Here's the JavaScript code to generate the menu:

```
var sections = document.querySelectorAll('section');
var navMenu = document.getElementById('nav-menu');
var menuList = document.createElement('ul');
var topLevelItems = [];

sections.forEach(function(section) {
  // create menu item for section
  var menuItem = document.createElement('li');
  var link = document.createElement('a');
  link.textContent = section.dataset.nav;
  link.href = '#' + section.id;
  menuItem.appendChild(link);
  
  // add sub-menu items for sub-sections
  var subSections = section.querySelectorAll(':scope > section');
  if (subSections.length > 0) {
    var subMenuList = document.createElement('ul');
    subSections.forEach(function(subSection) {
      var subMenuItem = document.createElement('li');
      var subLink = document.createElement('a');
      subLink.textContent = subSection.dataset.nav;
      subLink.href = '#' + subSection.id;
      subMenuItem.appendChild(subLink);
      subMenuList.appendChild(subMenuItem);
    });
    menuItem.appendChild(subMenuList);
    menuItem.classList.add('has-submenu');
    menuItem.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
      e.preventDefault();
      this.classList.toggle('open');
    });
  }
  
  // add menu item to top-level or sub-menu
  if (section.parentElement.tagName === 'BODY') {
    topLevelItems.push(menuItem);
  } else {
    var parentMenuItem = navMenu.querySelector('li a[href="#' + section.parentElement.id + '"]').parentElement;
    if (!parentMenuItem.querySelector('ul')) {
      var submenu = document.createElement('ul');
      parentMenuItem.appendChild(submenu);
      parentMenuItem.classList.add('has-submenu');
      parentMenuItem.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
        e.preventDefault();
        this.classList.toggle('open');
      });
    }
    parentMenuItem.querySelector('ul').appendChild(menuItem);
  }
});

topLevelItems.forEach(function(item) {
  menuList.appendChild(item);
});
navMenu.appendChild(menuList);
```

3. We need to add CSS styles to the menu items to make them look like a navigation menu. We can use the following styles to add padding, margin, background color, border, and other visual effects to the menu items.

```
#nav-menu {
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  background-color: #fff;
  padding: 20px;
  width: 200px;
  overflow-y: scroll;
  border-right: 1px solid #ddd;
}

#nav-menu ul {
  list-style: none;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}

#nav-menu li {
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  position: relative;
  cursor: pointer;
}

#nav-menu a {
  display: block;
  padding: 5px 10px;
  color: #333;
  text-decoration: none;
}

#nav-menu a:hover {
  background-color: #f5f5f5;
}

#nav-menu .has-submenu a:before {
  content: '';
  display: inline-block;
  margin-right: 10px;
  width: 12px;
  height: 12px;
  background-image: url('undevelop.svg');
  background-size: contain;
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
}

#nav-menu .has-submenu.open > a:before {
  background-image: url('develop.svg');
}

#nav-menu ul ul {
  margin-left: 20px;
}

#nav-menu .active {
  color: red;
}

#nav-menu .partial {
  color: blue;
}
```

4. Finally, we need to write JavaScript code to change the color of the menu items based on the scrolling position of the page. We can use the `getBoundingClientRect` method to get the position of each section element relative to the viewport, and then check if the top or bottom of the section is within the viewport. If the top of the section is above the viewport and the bottom of the section is below the viewport, we consider the section to be partially in view. If the top of the section is below the viewport, we consider the section to be not in view. If the top of the section is within the viewport, we consider the section to be in view. Here's the JavaScript code to change the color of the menu items:

```
var menuItems = document.querySelectorAll('#nav-menu a');

window.addEventListener('scroll', function() {
  var scrollPos = window.scrollY;
  menuItems.forEach(function(item) {
    var section = document.querySelector(item.getAttribute('href'));
    var rect = section.getBoundingClientRect();
    if (rect.top >= 0 && rect.bottom <= window.innerHeight) {
      item.classList.add('active');
      item.classList.remove('partial');
    } else if (rect.top < 0 && rect.bottom > 0) {
      item.classList.remove('active');
      item.classList.add('partial');
    } else {
      item.classList.remove('active');
      item.classList.remove('partial');
    }
  });
});
```

