Dijkstra's algorithm is an efficient algorithm for finding the shortest path in a graph with non-negative edge weights. Here is a Java implementation of the algorithm:

```java
import java.util.*;

public class ShortestPath {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Define a graph as an adjacency list
        Map<Integer, List<Edge>> graph = new HashMap<>();
        graph.put(1, Arrays.asList(new Edge(2, 7), new Edge(3, 9), new Edge(6, 14)));
        graph.put(2, Arrays.asList(new Edge(1, 7), new Edge(3, 10), new Edge(4, 15)));
        graph.put(3, Arrays.asList(new Edge(1, 9), new Edge(2, 10), new Edge(4, 11), new Edge(6, 2)));
        graph.put(4, Arrays.asList(new Edge(2, 15), new Edge(3, 11), new Edge(5, 6)));
        graph.put(5, Arrays.asList(new Edge(4, 6), new Edge(6, 9)));
        graph.put(6, Arrays.asList(new Edge(1, 14), new Edge(3, 2), new Edge(5, 9)));

        // Find the shortest path from node 1 to all other nodes
        Map<Integer, Integer> distances = shortestPath(graph, 1);

        // Print the distances
        for (int node : distances.keySet()) {
            System.out.println("Shortest distance from node 1 to node " + node + " is " + distances.get(node));
        }
    }

    private static Map<Integer, Integer> shortestPath(Map<Integer, List<Edge>> graph, int source) {
        // Initialize distances
        Map<Integer, Integer> distances = new HashMap<>();
        for (int node : graph.keySet()) {
            distances.put(node, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        }
        distances.put(source, 0);

        // Initialize visited set and priority queue
        Set<Integer> visited = new HashSet<>();
        PriorityQueue<NodeDistance> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();
        pq.offer(new NodeDistance(source, 0));

        // Iterate through priority queue until it is empty
        while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
            NodeDistance nodeDistance = pq.poll();
            int node = nodeDistance.getNode();
            int distance = nodeDistance.getDistance();

            // Skip visited nodes
            if (visited.contains(node)) {
                continue;
            }

            // Update distances and add unvisited neighbors to priority queue
            for (Edge edge : graph.get(node)) {
                int neighbor = edge.getNode();
                int edgeWeight = edge.getWeight();
                int totalDistance = distance + edgeWeight;
                if (totalDistance < distances.get(neighbor)) {
                    distances.put(neighbor, totalDistance);
                    pq.offer(new NodeDistance(neighbor, totalDistance));
                }
            }

            // Mark node as visited
            visited.add(node);
        }

        return distances;
    }

    private static class Edge {
        private final int node;
        private final int weight;

        public Edge(int node, int weight) {
            this.node = node;
            this.weight = weight;
        }

        public int getNode() {
            return node;
        }

        public int getWeight() {
            return weight;
        }
    }

    private static class NodeDistance implements Comparable<NodeDistance> {
        private final int node;
        private final int distance;

        public NodeDistance(int node, int distance) {
            this.node = node;
            this.distance = distance;
        }

        public int getNode() {
            return node;
        }

        public int getDistance() {
            return distance;
        }

        @Override
        public int compareTo(NodeDistance o) {
            return Integer.compare(distance, o.distance);
        }
    }

}
```

The program defines a graph as an adjacency list, with each key representing a node and each value representing a list of outgoing edges. It then finds the shortest path from a source node to all other nodes using Dijkstra's algorithm, which initializes distances to all nodes as infinity and the distance to the source node as 0. It then uses a priority queue to select the node with the shortest distance and updates the distances to its neighbors if a shorter path is found. The algorithm terminates when all nodes have been visited or the destination node has been reached. The program returns a map of node distances, which can be printed to the console.

