1. Define a struct for your linked list node. This struct should contain a value and two indices representing the previous and next nodes in the list.
```rust
struct Node<T> {
    value: T,
    prev: Option<usize>,
    next: Option<usize>,
}
```

2. Define a struct for your linked list. This struct should contain a fixed-size array for the nodes, two indices representing the head and tail nodes, and a counter for the number of nodes in the list.
```rust
struct LinkedList<T> {
    nodes: [Node<T>; MAX_SIZE],
    head: Option<usize>,
    tail: Option<usize>,
    size: usize,
}
```

3. Implement methods for your linked list struct that add, remove, and search for nodes in the list. For example, here is an implementation of a method to add a new node to the list while maintaining order:
```rust
fn add(&mut self, value: T) {
    let mut current = self.head;
    let mut prev = None;

    // Find the correct location to insert the new node
    while let Some(current_idx) = current {
        let current_node = &self.nodes[current_idx];

        if current_node.value >= value {
            break;
        }

        prev = Some(current_idx);
        current = current_node.next;
    }

    // Create the new node and insert it into the list
    let new_node = Node {
        value: value,
        prev: prev,
        next: current,
    };

    let new_node_idx = self.size;
    self.nodes[new_node_idx] = new_node;

    if let Some(prev_idx) = prev {
        self.nodes[prev_idx].next = Some(new_node_idx);
    } else {
        self.head = Some(new_node_idx);
    }

    if let Some(current_idx) = current {
        self.nodes[current_idx].prev = Some(new_node_idx);
    } else {
        self.tail = Some(new_node_idx);
    }

    self.size += 1;
}
```

