        this.size = size;
    }
}
```

Next, you'll need to create a list of parties with their respective IDs and party sizes. You can do this manually, or read in from a file/database.

```
List<Party> parties = new ArrayList<>();
parties.add(new Party(1, 2));
parties.add(new Party(2, 4));
parties.add(new Party(3, 6));
parties.add(new Party(4, 8));
```

Now comes the tricky part - you need to allocate tables to each party in the most efficient way possible. One possible algorithm could be:

1. Sort the tables in ascending order of their seat capacities.
2. Sort the parties in descending order of their party sizes.
3. For each party:
   1. Find the smallest table that can accommodate the party size.
   2. If such a table exists, assign the party to the table and remove the table from the list of available tables.
   3. If no such table exists, find the smallest combination of tables that can accommodate the party size.
   4. If such a combination exists, assign the party to the combination of tables and remove the tables from the list of available tables.
   5. If no such combination exists, the party cannot be accommodated.

Here's the code that implements this algorithm:

```
// Step 1: Sort tables by seat capacity
tables.sort((t1, t2) -> t1.seats - t2.seats);

// Step 2: Sort parties by size
parties.sort((p1, p2) -> p2.size - p1.size);

// Step 3: Allocate tables to parties
for (Party party : parties) {
    boolean tableAssigned = false;
    for (Table table : tables) {
        if (table.seats >= party.size) {
            System.out.println("Party " + party.id + " assigned to table " + table.id);
            tables.remove(table);
            tableAssigned = true;
            break;
        }
    }
    if (!tableAssigned) {
        List<Table> combination = findTableCombination(tables, party.size);
        if (combination != null) {
            System.out.print("Party " + party.id + " assigned to tables ");
            for (Table table : combination) {
                System.out.print(table.id + " ");
                tables.remove(table);
            }
            System.out.println();
            tableAssigned = true;
        }
    }
    if (!tableAssigned) {
        System.out.println("Party " + party.id + " cannot be accommodated");
    }
}

// Helper method to find the smallest combination of tables that can accommodate a party
private static List<Table> findTableCombination(List<Table> tables, int partySize) {
    for (int i = 0; i < tables.size(); i++) {
        List<Table> combination = new ArrayList<>();
        int remainingSeats = partySize - tables.get(i).seats;
        if (remainingSeats == 0) {
            combination.add(tables.get(i));
            return combination;
        }
        for (int j = i + 1; j < tables.size(); j++) {
            if (remainingSeats <= tables.get(j).seats) {
                combination.add(tables.get(i));
                combination.add(tables.get(j));
                return combination;
            }
            remainingSeats -= tables.get(j).seats;
        }
    }
    return null;
}
```

Note that this algorithm is not guaranteed to be optimal in all cases, but it should work well for most practical purposes. You may need to tweak it or come up with a different algorithm depending on your specific requirements.

