Certainly! Here's an implementation of the merge sort algorithm in C#:
```
public static void MergeSort(int[] array)
{
    if (array.Length <= 1)
    {
        return;
    }

    int middleIndex = array.Length / 2;
    int[] leftArray = new int[middleIndex];
    int[] rightArray = new int[array.Length - middleIndex];

    for (int i = 0; i < middleIndex; i++)
    {
        leftArray[i] = array[i];
    }

    for (int i = middleIndex; i < array.Length; i++)
    {
        rightArray[i - middleIndex] = array[i];
    }

    MergeSort(leftArray);
    MergeSort(rightArray);
    Merge(leftArray, rightArray, array);
}

private static void Merge(int[] leftArray, int[] rightArray, int[] resultArray)
{
    int leftIndex = 0;
    int rightIndex = 0;
    int resultIndex = 0;

    while (leftIndex < leftArray.Length && rightIndex < rightArray.Length)
    {
        if (leftArray[leftIndex] <= rightArray[rightIndex])
        {
            resultArray[resultIndex] = leftArray[leftIndex];
            leftIndex++;
        }
        else
        {
            resultArray[resultIndex] = rightArray[rightIndex];
            rightIndex++;
        }
        resultIndex++;
    }

    while (leftIndex < leftArray.Length)
    {
        resultArray[resultIndex] = leftArray[leftIndex];
        leftIndex++;
        resultIndex++;
    }

    while (rightIndex < rightArray.Length)
    {
        resultArray[resultIndex] = rightArray[rightIndex];
        rightIndex++;
        resultIndex++;
    }
}
```
Here's how it works:
1. The `MergeSort` method takes an array as input and recursively sorts it using the merge sort algorithm.
2. If the array has only one element or is empty, it is already sorted, so the method simply returns.
3. Otherwise, the method finds the middle index of the array and creates two new arrays, `leftArray` and `rightArray`, which contain the left and right halves of the original array.
4. The `MergeSort` method is called recursively on `leftArray` and `rightArray`.
5. The `Merge` method takes the `leftArray` and `rightArray` and combines them into a single sorted array, `resultArray`.
6. The `Merge` method uses three index variables, `leftIndex`, `rightIndex`, and `resultIndex`, to keep track of the current position in each of the arrays.
7. The `while` loop in the `Merge` method compares the elements at the current positions in `leftArray` and `rightArray` and adds the smaller element to `resultArray`, incrementing the appropriate index variable.
8. After one of the arrays is exhausted, the remaining elements from the other array are added to `resultArray`.
9. Once `Merge` has finished, the sorted `resultArray` is returned to the calling method.
To use the `MergeSort` method, simply call it with the array you want to sort:
```
int[] array = { 5, 3, 8, 4, 2 };
MergeSort(array);
```
After the method finishes, the `array` will be sorted in ascending order.

